On Wed, Mar 25, 2015 at 10:37:33AM -0700, pbrunet wrote:
> > @@ -14,6 +16,7 @@ template<bool V0> struct all_of<V0> {
> >  };
> >  
> >  template<bool... V> struct any_of;
> > +template<> struct any_of<> : std::integral_constant<bool, true> {};
> 
> It is not the case in Python and in C++. It seem to be more "logic" to me as none of them is "true".

Yes, I am... 100% faulty on this one.

I see you tried to mitigate that, but I still prefer to set the default in the arg to `None` then set a fresh default in the function body.

```python
def send_email(messages, backend_kwargs=None, **kwargs):
    final_kwargs = {}
    if backend_kwargs:
        final_kwargs.update(backend_kwargs)
    
    final_kwargs.update(kwargs)
    ...
```

Can we reverse it, so that Dynamic Permission inherits from Permission instead....this will make it easier to remove.

Could be done with:
```python
class Permission(_Permission):
   allow_by_default = False

   def _load_permission(self):
       if not self._allow_by_default:
          self._permissions.needs.update(self.explicity_needs)
       #....


class DynamicPermission(Permission)
     allow_by_default = True

     def __init__(...):
         warnings.warn("DynamicPermission will scheduled for removal", PendingDeprecationWarning)

@tseaver in python 2, if they happen to pass in a sample rate of say...16000.0, then `16000.0//10` returns `1600.0` which then fails when you call `read(1600.0)`.

`TypeError: 'float' object cannot be interpreted as an index`.
A rare case I suppose.

@lukesneeringer @tseaver 

1. What sort of `@Retry` should I bake into this `next()` call on the iterator?
1. I realized that **after** this `next(entry_iter)` keeps going, which surprised me. We should probably have a `max_results` keyword as well?

@raghavg7796 No. Since most of the code is common in both `predict` and `predict_probability`, I was suggesting something like:

```python
def _predict():
     # common code

def predict():
     # call _predict and do something with results

def predict_probability():
     # call _predict and do something with the values
```
or 
```python
def predict_probabilities():
     # compute the probabilities

def predict():
     # call predict_probabilities and use that to give the final predictions
```

not sure. I'll have to dig in to figure it out. 
@jcsp Do you have any insight here?
On first reading it must be that ceph is expressing time in a seconds.nanoseconds and if we just used float(val) we'd get an incorrect coercion based on seconds.deci_centi_milli_.._nano. Does that make sense?

I'm not sure about placing the `except AttributeError` so far from the line that's meant to cause it. I'd prefer either:
```python
try:
    output_shape = self._output_shape
except AttributeError:
    return input_shape
else:
    ...
```
or setting `self._output_shape` to `None` in the constructor if `output_shape` is `None`. That way, `_output_shape` is always defined when `get_output_shape_for` wasn't overwritten and can simply be checked for.

